            user: 'tRG55cd9+jQdEon/p97yQw==',
            reviewDate: 'May 6, 2024',
            semester: 'fall 2023',
            review: "This review pertains to CS7641 taken in the spring semester 2024.\n(I would recommend to only consider reviews from Fall 2023 on, as this is the closest to where this graduate course currently stands)\nThe course has scaled enormously when it comes to the number of students registering and taking it. This probably applies to the program as a whole. Dr. Starner referred to this as a \"Success Failure\".\nSomeone recently said \"..This course should be named Graduate Introduction to Machine Learning\" - not too far off!\nFor this semester's iteration, there is no midterm. The Staff is interested/invested in iterating and improving the course over time to improve the quality of life and overall learning experience. With that said, You should expect that iteration, improvement/progress takes time.\nNot having to worry about a midterm while also wrapping up an assignment is a big improvement over the 2023 Fall Semester.\nThis semester we were mainly graded on 4 assignments that covered supervised learning, unsupervised learning, and reinforcement learning. Additionally we were graded on a final exam that is in a Multiple Choice, Multiple Answer Format.\nThe syllabus for this semester also covered a reading/writing quiz (on how to read and write scientific papers) and a problem set which is a good starting point for your studying, and participating in discussions was also a factor.\nThis course might be easy for some, based on their prior experience in ML or Comp Sci.\nHowever, I would recommend that anyone attempting this course to manage expectations up front, and adapt the proper mindset.\nThe proper mindset, IMHO, is one of wanting to learn and understand. Your understanding will be formed by reading the main book (ML - Tom Mitchell), the lectures, papers, and the blogs that were made available this semester. Additionally, you can find more papers that you can then also use as references or inform more novel approaches in your methodology.\nTo further solidify understanding of the material it will help to discuss the things learned with the students in the proper discussion forums (Ed / Slack)\nExpect to get out what you put in (almost sounds cliche, I know). More specifically, when working on the assignments, the professor and TA staff expect you to thoughtfully and thoroughly analyze your observations that are afforded through each of the experimental methodologies you set up for your assignments. Each assignment will cover algorithms and techniques used for supervised, unsupervised, and reinforcement learning. Expect to discuss limitations, short comings, improvements.\nExpect to get your assignment requirements from the assignment description, FAQs, and office hours that are held twice a week.\nExpect to spend time on structuring your research/experiments.\nExpect to spend time on iteration across algorithms/techniques as it comes to hyperparameter search/optimization.\nExpect to observe/discuss/find various/different aspects of convergence and complexity as it applies to the ML topics.\nExpect to structure your analysis when converting it to a report. While there is no one format that's required, a scientific format such as IEEE is definitely encouraged. If you have the time to invest into LaTeX that could also be worth it.\nExpect to use Python or Java as well as libraries such as sklearn,mlrose,bettermdptools.\nExpect to hit roadblocks or errors as you setup your methodology and work through those.\nExpect to be encouraged to learn, and that your algorithms might not be as \"performant\" as you would like. Yet, this empirical information is great for writing up your analysis.\nExpect to be able to talk about your metrics in form of tabular or visual graphs.\nIf you become familiar with sklearn,matplotlib,seasborn (sns), pandas,yellow brick that's going to help.\nDuring the course of your assignments, expect to form hypotheses and provide supporting information that will confirm them.\nSome of the concerns mentioned below are definitely still valid. But this shouldn't detract from your goals of taking this graduate course.\nExpect that you will not see an autograder, and that TAs will read/grade your papers. And Expect that this will take time.\nExpect to take the feedback you will receive to inform the changes/improvements of your next assignment's analysis.\nI used Google colab and it's worked well for me. There will be some additional steps required when you cant simply import a library to execute your methodology.\nWhile the outcomes of this course can be applied to industry, especially when it comes to experimental methodology, analysis, reporting, do not expect that this course will set you up to be an ML Engineer. Nevertheless, I do think it has potential for you to become more of a practitioner.\nExpect that the grading will be different than most courses you might have taken. Expect that, more often than not, staying above the average is a good trend/indicator for how you far in the course.\nFor some reason, I did not know this when I first attempted this course in Fall 2023. I dropped it.\nI took it again this spring, and took a leap of faith to hang on until the end. It was worth it.\nWith the knowledge I have now, I'm actually interested in further investigating ML topics, and possibly contributing in some form at work. (I work at a Data and AI company)\nThis was the last requirement for me to graduate. While this course was the hardest I've taken at GA Tech, I recommend this course.",
