            reviewDate: 'May 6, 2024',
            semester: 'spring 2023',
            review: "Review is for Spring 2024:\nHaving experience in ML certainly helps going into this course, as I can only imagine how overwhelming may be for the uninitiated. Even with a prior background in ML, this course is not a walk in the park by any stretch.\nAnticipate allotting >20 hours per week on writing/debugging code, running that code, and analyzing/interpreting results.  This process can feel painfully iterative at times.  Pay close attention to course announcements related to the assignments, as these will often provide clues for what is expected in each assignment's corresponding report.  However, there is no roadmap or template here; this course focuses on experimenting with different parameters and methods, justifying why those experiments were chosen, what were the hypotheses, and why they were interesting.  But no one is going to say \"You MUST pick this particular ML algorithm for training against this specific dataset, and set these exact hyperparameters to X, Y, Z\".\nAs far as the reports: give yourself time (as in, 8+ hours).  It can be challenging to stay within the page limit, so adjusting page margins, font sizes, image scaling, etc. can help. Use LaTeX for this.  A main point of emphasis in this course is communicating the results and explaining WHY the results are what they are, not just objectively describing them (as in: Curve A appears greater than Curve B vs. this is what causes Curve A to be greater than Curve B).\nOverall, this course is a ton of effort so unless you either work extremely efficiently or have an overabundance of spare time, probably do not take it in parallel to most others in the program.\nThe main area for improvement, in my opinion, would be in the timeliness of grading.  Realistically, there are >500 or whatever number of students each semester, so reading reports while providing meaningful feedback takes time.  Still, I enjoyed this course (especially now that it's over), the staff seemed genuinely interested in helping students succeed, and there are many opportunities to dive deeper into ML topics while sharpening one's report-writing skills.\nJust a word of caution: when given the choice to select your own datasets and algorithms, try not to pick things that are especially overcomplicated. No one is going to be more impressed that you processed a dataset with 1.5 million rows vs. one that is just 2,500 rows.  What's more important is that you can explain your results and what you did to get them.",
