            user: 'Georgia Tech Student',
            reviewDate: 'December 13, 2020',
            semester: 'fall 2020',
            review: "This class has good and bad elements to it, but I would say overall bad and my least favorite class in the program so far.\nThe good part is that the assignments are very practical and can be approached like a research project with exploration and use of any tools you like (instead of writing your own algorithms). I was inspired to use some of the techniques at my work. The tests also focus less on rote memorization than synthesis of ideas which is cool. The instructors seem to have fun teaching, which is encouraging.\nThe bad part is that the assignments say they encourage exploration but are really graded on a secret rubric that you must find out from office hours! You could waste a lot of time going in the wrong direction on the assignments and get a bad grade because you could not divine the secret rubric's requirements. While the instructor may be enjoying himself on Piazza (good to have fun), some of his responses end up being a vague and cynical dismissal of the question when a clear answer would have sufficed.\nIf you are in the ML specialization, you have to take the course so just go into it with an open mind and be ready to sink a lot of time into this class. If not, I would spend one of your 10 course slots on something else.",
